# Job Salary Prediction 

## Questions Answered
1. Which industries pay the most / least?
2. Does more education lead to higher salary?
3. Does location matter?
4. Which factor matters most for salary — job title, experience, or skills?
5. Build a model that predicts salary.

## Key Findings
- Industry and location show statistically real salary differences (ANOVA).
- Education level does not meaningfully affect salary in this dataset.
- Among job_title, experience, and skills — experience_years is the strongest predictor; skills_count is negligible.
- Final model: Random Forest — R² = 0.96, average error (MAE) ≈ ₦,292.48. Outperformed Random Forest (R² = 0.91).

## Limitations
- `location` ranked as the top salary driver in Random Forest importance — suspicious, since real data would expect experience or job title to dominate. Suggests an artificial/simplified data-generation process.
- No external validation — tested only on a held-out split of the same dataset, not real-world data.
- Categorical variables (job_title, industry, location) one-hot encoded with no regularization which may cause some overfitting risk

## Conclusion
Industry and location show statistically real salary differences (ANOVA); education level does not meaningfully affect salary.
Among job_title, experience, and skills, experience_years is the strongest predictor. 
The final model predicts salary accurately, off by about ₦7,292 on average, and holds up on spot-checks — though conclusions are limited by the dataset being synthetic rather than real-world.
